      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Park_Slope"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "The neighborhood’s Carnegie library branch, built 1905–06, now serves as the Park Slope Public Library and is a city landmark.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        6
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Park_Slope"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "In 1853, the Brooklyn City Railroad introduced horse‑drawn railcars, giving Park Slope early competition to the main railroad.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        1
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Park_Slope"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "The 1906 Prospect Park branch library was originally named the “Prospect branch” until 1975.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        3
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Park_Slope"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "Park Slope earned the American Planning Association’s “Greatest Neighborhoods in America” title in 2007 for its architecture and diverse community.",
